text: I'm a Christian and I can confidently say I hate almost all Christian films I've seen. They are made by Christians for Christians. they paint atheism as the enemy when that is absolutely not the case. They spew the same generic "God loves you" type themes but never fully explore the depth of God or the reality of his presence. Their sole purpose is to further the divide between Christianity and atheism by showing the same general themes with absolutely nothing new to say. Like if I was an atheist watching these movies I would be so appalled by religion and how "in your face" these movies are. These movies make it look like once you're a Christian you don't have any issues because everything will eventually be good because God is good. I agree with that to an extent. Yes, if you are a Christian and die that way then you will go to heaven for eternity which is, of course, a happy ending. But God isn't just gonna not allow any bad to happen to you. Like every traumatic incident and all the pain I've felt in my life have made me the person I am. I know that through the bad and the good God is still God. he is Good and merciful and powerful and forgiving. For any of you Christians out there, I don't know the exact passage, but Jesus comes to Thomas and tells him he has resurrected and all that stuff. Thomas doubts him and Jesus tells him to put his fingers in his pierced hands. This means that Jesus's spiritual body still has the scars of his pain and the trials he went through. There's power in suffering. I think Christians need to start understanding and believing that before we start preaching this ooy gooy lifestyle where all is unicorns and rainbows when all the disciples were persecuted for their beliefs (most to the point of death)  and Peter was crucified on an upside-down cross because he didn't think he was worthy enough to die the death of his savior. In conclusion, I just think there needs to be more 'realistic' Christian¬†movies that show the actual life of real devoted Christians that choose not to just say the words and then use the church as a status or facade. We need movies that don't try to act like any other religions or beliefs are our enemy. We are called to love so why do our movies not show what a genuine loving relationship with the lord is like. Sorry that this was so long. It's just this is something I'm very passionate about and I needed to get off my chest. It just angers me to see movies like this that do the opposite of what they intend to do. In their pretentiousness, they divide more than they unify.
author: Ryan Schlaud

text: The bible indicates a total of 10 people in the Old and New Testament being brought back from what would be considered brain death and some supposedly even after severe decomposition would have begun, several from their graves days after burial. That is what's entirely different then modern day accounts of people being prayed back from the dead, the accounts we here about are people who are given emergency medical treatment within anywhere from 15- 30 minutes after their heart stops and in this case the person was submerged in ice cold water and remember the saying for hypothermia victims " they aren't dead until they are warm and dead" . Apparently due to very cold temperatures Smith avoided very much damage to his brain and was never really brain dead, once you reach the medical criteria of brain death there is no coming back. I don't believe people understand the difference between coma, vegetative and prolonged vegetative state and brain death. There is a rule of thumb we should keep in mind , under normal conditions after about six minutes without any blood-flow brain cells begin to die and there will be brain damage after ten minutes brain death occurs. If a person is hypothermic *their metabolism is slowed down and their brain is protected to some limited degree from when normally brain death would set in.

text: New research shows that cold water drowning victims can be brought back to life as long as two hours after they drown if the right steps are taken. That means even if the heart has stopped beating and the victims' brains aren't getting the oxygen we all need to stay alive. Once the body detects an impending cold-water immersion, it attempts to thwart the cold and preserve blood flow to the brain and internal organs. The heart rate slows down, decreasing oxygen demand. And capillaries in the hands and feet begin to tighten, squeezing blood to the core of the body and brain, where it‚Äôs needed most.  That response gives cold water drowning victims the equivalent of a second life ‚Äî if rescuers know how to treat them. Research shows the key is to call 911 and start¬†CPR¬†immediately, without trying to warm the body. Once victims reach the hospital, doctors can slowly warm and restore blood flow, often bringing the dead back to life.  And the difference between life and death for cold water and regular drowning victims is more than a matter of minutes.¬†Dr. Robert Helm, a New Hampshire cardiac surgeon tells of a 3-year-old girl who was resuscitated after nearly 50 minutes. And it‚Äôs not just young children who get a second chance in cold water drownings. Helm also knows of a 32-year-old woman who was not resuscitated until nearly 80 minutes after her drowning. Being brought back to life might seem like the amazing part. But it‚Äôs the other part that‚Äôs truly miraculous: both victims recovered without a brain damage.  Why is that amazing? Drowning isn‚Äôt just an event that causes death. Often, drowning survivors suffer¬†brain damage¬†because of the amount of time their brains go without oxygen. That‚Äôs why more than¬†50 percent¬†of drowning victims who survive require hospitalization. And for every child who drowns, three suffer brain damage, according to the¬†Swims Foundation.  So as spring slowly comes this year, bringing with it the inevitable falls through ice, remember that cold water drownings don‚Äôt have to be a death sentence, nor a debilitating trauma. They just need to be treated differently than regular drownings. Doing so could give someone a second chance at life.
